  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Record of the City Gate Tower of Yeongju
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the Spring and Autumn Annals, the construction of cities is recorded twenty-four times, yet nearly all are censured—for they violated proper timing and departed from established standards. Even when recorded unfavorably, such accounts reveal how gravely the chronicler regarded the burden imposed upon the people. Should Confucius himself be born in this present age, and were a city built within proper measure, its construction undertaken at fitting season, and all work carried out in accordance with righteousness, surely he would record it with special commendation and praise. Would he merely pass it by?

    In the spring of Imsu, when Administrator Lee arrived to govern Yeongju, scarcely a month had passed before Japanese raiders struck. Thereafter, invasions followed upon one another—thirty-six times in succession. The people of Yeongju all crossed the river and fled westward, eking out bare survival with no thought of returning east. Yet when they heard that Administrator Lee would build this city, they returned together, eagerly hastening to aid the work. Hardly was the city completed when an alarm arose. The Administrator, having made modest preparations for defense, called the people into the city, arrayed his forces, and waited. The people's hearts grew firm; the enemy could do nothing against us.

    The work began in late autumn and was completed by winter solstice—truly accomplished in its proper season. Through gentle methods the people were led to forget their labors; without urgency, the work proceeded swiftly, and righteousness dwelt within it naturally. A city of three li, numbering no more than one hundred ramparts, cannot be called excessive in proportion. With these three conditions fulfilled, I wonder whether the great historians of our time will record the building of this city at Yeongju.

    When cities are recorded, it is because old walls are restored; when building is recorded, it is because something new is begun. This city, though it arose from the Administrator's temporary direction and design, revealed ancient artifacts when the earth was excavated—clear proof of its ancient foundation. Thus it should surely be recorded as a city. The fortification stands west of the prefectural seat, above the Cheongtongyeok station, with three sides steep and inaccessible, only the southern face permitting ascent.

    Administrator Lee is my friend of the same generation. I admired how he undertook this great work without burdening the people, and so when he requested this record, I dared not refuse him by claiming my writing was poor.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Spring and Autumn Annals (《춘추》) is the authoritative historical chronicle of the state of Lu, traditionally edited by Confucius.
  - key: ''
    value: Imsu year refers to 1482 in the Gregorian calendar, during the Joseon Dynasty.
  - key: ''
    value: The thirty-six Japanese raids reference the repeated倭寇 (waegu) invasions of Korea's southern coast during the 15th century.
  - key: ''
    value: The city of three li (about 1.2 kilometers) with one hundred ramparts represents modest but adequate fortifications for the period.
